Living a bachelor's’ life and testamentary preference for children above all is not yet out of fashion in Comoros.
Among the younger population, having only one spouse is a common occurrence among women. Men do not often break marriages. Up to 98 percent of both women and
men do not see any problems with this. Meeting someone special for people over the age of 66 is a bit problematic—if only because an average of less than 10 percent of the total population is in that age bracket today. 5.3.8 Husbands’ prestige across the Comoros archipelago The greater shoal is home to the most traditional islands. So common elements involve a husband's high pedestal surrounded by a hazel halo when he is compared to the wife. Contrasts and heavy dominance within the family are as old as the indigenous clans of the archipelago. 38.6 percent of the wives do not see their position as being satisfactory in the family. A large proportion of them believe that the husband should not be called properly as a “master”. Thus, 22.7 percent intend to change husbands if necessary, because they tend to be deficient.
